Charles Schwab Bank Review: Checking, Savings and CDs - NerdWallet


























































 
 

Get your free credit score.Log inSign upSign up
 






Advertiser Disclosure


Charles Schwab Bank Review: Checking, Savings and CDs 


 


Amber Murakami-Fester 

March 30, 2017




















SavedSave 



Banking, Banks & Credit Unions





  

Charles Schwab Bank
NerdWallet’s rating: 4.5 / 5.0

Learn moreat SchwabSure, it’s known primarily as an investing platform, but Charles Schwab also offers banking products, such as checking accounts, savings accounts and certificates of deposit. And here’s the thing — they’re each pretty darn good.
The bottom line

With no fees or minimum balances, High Yield Investor checking and savings accounts offer stress-free banking.
Its ATM coverage is superior to most competitors.
Interest rates on High Yield Investor checking and savings accounts are low, but they’re stellar on certificates of deposit.
The difficulty of depositing cash and lack of branch access mean Charles Schwab isn’t for everyone.
Be aware the bank will do a hard inquiry on your credit when you apply for an account.

» MORE: Best banks for international travel




Our Ratings




Checking account


Savings account


Certificates of deposit (CDs)


Customer experience


Overdraft fees


Overall




Read on for more information about Charles Schwab’s checking and savings products, CDs, customer experience and fees.
Checking

5.0 / 5.0
It’s not easy to deposit cash into a High Yield Investor checking account, and you’ll find better interest rates at other institutions. But this account makes up for its blemishes with one of the best ATM reimbursement policies in the game.
You must have a Schwab One brokerage account to open the checking account, but you’re not under any obligation to use the brokerage account.
Transfers between any of your Schwab accounts happen in real time, but moving money to or from an outside account can take up to five business days the first time, and roughly one or two business days after that. Keep in mind that Schwab will conduct a hard inquiry on your credit if you choose to apply for an account.




ProsCons




No monthly fee or minimum opening deposit.Unlimited ATM fee reimbursements, domestically and abroad.Unlimited check writing.
Difficult to deposit cash: You’ll have to convert it into a money order or a cashier’s check and submit it via mail or mobile check deposit.Other banks offer higher interest rates than Schwab’s 0.10%.




» MORE: NerdWallet’s best checking accounts
Savings

4.0 / 5.0
The High Yield Investor savings account isn’t flashy, and its low rates mean your money will grow more quickly elsewhere. But because it doesn’t charge monthly fees or require a minimum balance, it’s simple and stress-free to use.




ProsCons




No monthly fees or minimum balance requirements.Sweeps uninvested cash from your Schwab One brokerage account at the end of the day so it can earn interest.
Relatively low APY of 0.14%.




» MORE: NerdWallet’s best savings accounts
Certificates of deposit

5.0 / 5.0
Charles Schwab’s certificates of deposit, whose terms range from one month to 10 years, come with top-notch interest rates. They often fluctuate, though, so call the bank to confirm them before you open a CD.




ProsCons




Offers APYs of 0.70%-2.80%, outshining many competitors.Large range of term lengths, from one month to 10 years.
Require minimum balance of $1,000.




» MORE: Best CD rates
Customer experience

4.5 / 5.0
Charles Schwab provides customer service through multiple avenues, including Twitter and 24/7 chat support. Its phone support is available between 4 a.m. and 8 p.m. PT on weekdays and between 6 a.m. and 7:30 p.m. PT on weekends. And its clean website and favorably rated apps also make for a good customer experience. 
If you prefer to bank in person, though, Schwab is hard to access. It has roughly 330 brokerage branches across the country, and the banking services you can complete at them are limited.
Overdraft fees

3.0 / 5.0
Charles Schwab’s overdraft policy is generous for card transactions but tough on noncard payments. When you overdraft with your card, Schwab automatically pulls money from your linked Schwab One brokerage account or your Schwab savings account, free of charge. If you don’t have enough money in either, Schwab will deny your debit card transaction and won’t charge an overdraft fee. You might also qualify for an overdraft line of credit at a rate of 13.74% as of March 29, 2017.
Beware, though: If you don’t have enough money in your accounts to cover checks or electronic withdrawals and payments, you’ll be hit with a $25 nonsufficient funds fee, up to $100 a day.
» MORE: Overdraft fees: What banks charge
Simple, stress-free banking
Banking with Charles Schwab is a no-brainer if you don’t pay much attention to checking and savings interest rates and don’t deposit cash too often. The lack of fees or minimum balances and the perk of unlimited ATM reimbursements mean you’ll be able to bank without constantly worrying about racking up avoidable charges. High CD rates and ample customer service also give Schwab a boost. Be careful of nonsufficient funds fees, and Charles Schwab bank should provide a smooth experience.
Amber Murakami-Fester is a staff writer at NerdWallet, a personal finance website. Email: amufe@nerdwallet.com. Twitter: @iamyams.
Updated March 30, 2017

Ratings methodology

NerdWallet’s overall ratings for banks and credit unions are weighted averages of several categories: checking, savings, certificates of deposit or credit union share certificates, customer experience and overdraft fees.
Factors we consider, depending on the category, include rates and fees, ATM and branch access, account features and limits, user-facing technology, customer service and innovation.
The stars represent ratings from poor (one star) to excellent (five stars). Ratings are rounded to the nearest half-star.

 




